If we have a class like the following:

```csharp
class Person
{
  public string Name { get; set; }
  public Address Address { get; set; }
  [...]
}
```

These fields will yield the warning CS8618 "non-nullable property xxx is uninitialized". The only way to keep these fields required, is (a) to assign them values in the constructor, or (b) initialize with dummy values in the lines that declares them:

```csharp
class Person
{
  public string Name { get; set; } = string.Empty;  // dummy value
  public Address Address { get; set; }

  public Person(Address address)
  {
     Address = address;   // assign in constructor
  }
}
```

But doing so has some problems:
- dummy values, such as the empty string, defeat the original purpose of controlling that the programmer forgot to pass a value
- a class can have many fields, and adding a bunch of parameters to a constructor makes the code awfully less readable

Thus, it would be much more interesting if the "required" behavior of these fields was such that any caller creating an instance is required to pass a value, as in the following code:

```csharp
// compiles without errors or warnings
var myPerson = new Person
{
  Name = "Pablo",
  Address = new Address(...)
}

// yields a warning that the member `Address` is required yet uninitialized
var anotherPerson = new Person
{
  Name = "John"
}
```

